  <Subject Subject_ID="300010663">
    <Parent_Relationships>
      <Preferred_Parent>
        <Parent_Subject_ID>300010662</Parent_Subject_ID>
        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>porcelain (material) [300010662], ceramic (material) [300235507], ceramic and ceramic by product [300151340], clay by product [300010462], clay [300010439], inorganic material [300010360], materials by composition [300212963], materials (substances) [300010358], Materials (hierarchy name) [300010357], Materials Facet [300264091]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Type of porcelain material comprising white china clay, or "kaolin," and "petuntse," which is a naturally fusible feldspathic rock. It is "hard fired" at the relatively high temperature of around 1450 degrees centigrade. It was developed first in China and produced in Europe after 1700.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000045873/Oxford Companion to the Decorative Arts (1985)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Se refiere a un tipo de porcelana hecha de arcilla blanca de China, o "caolín," y el "petuntse” como se le llama a la piedra de China la cual es naturalmente una roca de tipo feldespático. Son cocidas a temperaturas relativamente altas, alrededor de los 1450 grados centígrados." Fue descubierta primero en China y posteriormente producida en Europa después del 1700.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Verwijst naar een porseleinsoort die is gemaakt van witte porseleinaarde, of 'kaolien' en 'petuntse', een natuurlijk smeltbaar veldspaathoudend gesteente. Het wordt 'hardgebakken' op een relatief hoge temperatuur van ongeveer 1450 graden Celsius. Het werd voor het eerst gemaakt in China en na 1700 in Europa geproduceerd.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指一種由白色瓷土（或稱「高嶺土」）和一種天然易熔的長石岩「瓷石（petuntse）」所製成的瓷。硬質瓷以攝氏約為1450度的相對高溫「硬燒（hard fired）」而成。首見於中國，自西元1700年後才在歐洲製造。 </Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
